Unlike home loans and other forms of secured lending, personal loans tend to be unsecured, meaning they generally don’t require collateral or a repayment guarantee. Instead, lenders typically analyze your earning capacity and credit history to determine whether you qualify for a personal loan.

People who aren’t earning enough, have no current income, or have poor credit scores generally don’t qualify for personal loans. So, they may have to seek out other forms of borrowing that come with no income verification. 

